@sowmyakth I guess the only procedure I can suggest to tell whether or not you have compiled enough empty fields is to check how quickly the correlation function (CF) converges to a stable pattern as you average over the CFs adding successive fields.  You could also just look at the standard deviation in the CF values across your six images (I'd probably advocate getting a few more too) to estimate how many you will need to co-add to reach a certain fractional uncertainty across the CF.

I'd probably advocate at least 16 or so, sampled, if possible, from an approximate 4x4 grid in the telescope field of view to cover the varying distortions.  But how many you need also depends on how large the fields were to start with, as smaller fields will yield noisier CF estimates.  You will see in the pull request #358 that Rachel referenced above that I went way beyond that for COSMOS and got as far as 92 fields before I finally got bored!  That was possibly overkill :)

